ty and staying power of remakes as a formative genre in filmmaking. The contributors show that the practice of remaking films dates back to the origins of cinema and the evolution of film markets. In fact, remakes were never so prevalent as during the Classic Hollywood period, when filmmaking had achieved its greatest degree of industrialization, and they continue to play a crucial role in the development of film genres generally. Offering a variety of historical, commercial, theoretical, and cultural perspectives on the remake, Dead Ringers is a valuable resource for students of film history and theory, as well as those interested in the cultural politics of the late twentieth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aFilm remakesxHistory and criticism. 0aMotion picturesxHistory. 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Popular Culture.2bisacsh1 aDurham, Carolyn A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aForrest, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aForrest, Jennifer, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGrindstaff, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarney, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKoos, Leonard R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKoos, Leonard R., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLeitch, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoth, Marty, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWelsch, Tricia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWilliams, Alan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe G